article.headline: Washington State 63, Arizona State 56
article.story: PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) -- Marcus Moore missed his first 10 shots, then scored all 12 of his points in the final 10:17 Thursday night to help lead Washington State past Arizona State 63-56. "I'm going to keep shooting, I can promise you that," Moore said with a grin. Jeff Varem led WSU (9-9, 3-5 Pacific-10) with 17 points. Two other pivotal Cougars were Shami Gill and Justin Bellegarde, who held Pac-10 scoring leader Ike Diogu to 13 points for Arizona State (8-9, 2-6). WSU coach Dick Bennett praised the defenders, saying they did "a very fine job." "It was probably one of his (Diogu's) lesser ball games, and we struggle if he's not going," ASU coach Rob Evans said. The 9-9 record is WSU's best after 18 games since a 10-8 start in 1996-97. The three conference wins matches WSU's total for the previous two seasons combined. Diogu's 13 points and five rebounds led the Sun Devils, but the points tied his season low, and the rebounds was his season low. Arizona State's scoring total was a season low, while the team's 24 turnovers were a season high. "We had some guys who didn't give the effort you have to have to win on the road," Evans said. The Cougars, who trailed most of the first half and led most of the second half, shot just 31 percent in the first half and fell behind 26-23 at the break. WSU shot 52 percent in the second half (40 percent for the game) and never trailed after Bellegarde capped an early 8-0 run in the second half to push WSU ahead 33-29. "It may not have been a work of art ... (but) it was an extremely hard-fought game," said Bennett, who has been critical of his team's effort at times. "I thought we played with an intensity that was missing last week and the week before. Thankfully, we got some shots to fall in the second half." Bellegarde, a little-used senior, tied his career high of eight points in his two seasons at Washington State. Combined with Gill, who scored eight points and had a team-high six rebounds before fouling out late in the game, Bellegarde helped hold Diogu well under his averages of 23 points and nine rebounds. WSU snapped a three-game losing streak, and a four-game losing streak against Arizona State. The Sun Devils won the previous three meetings by an average of 42 points. The Cougars play No. 9 Arizona (13-4, 5-3) at home on Saturday. "Any chance of Arizona taking us lightly just went out the window," Bennett noted.
